            [
                'title' => 'Never Too Old to Learn',
                'content' => "My grandmother got her GED at 78. She'd dropped out of school in the eighth grade to help on the family farm and always regretted it.\n\n\"I'm going to die educated,\" she announced one Thanksgiving. We thought she was joking.\n\nShe wasn't. She enrolled in classes, stayed up late studying, and asked her great-grandchildren to help her with math. The day she passed her exam, she cried harder than at any funeral she'd ever attended.\n\n\"I proved something to myself,\" she said. \"It doesn't matter how many years you waste. What matters is what you do with the years you have left.\"",
                'excerpt' => 'At 78, she finally got the education she\'d always wanted.',
                'category' => 'inspiration',
                'author_type' => AuthorType::Self,
                'tags' => ['education', 'age', 'determination', 'grandparents'],
            ],
            [
                'title' => 'From Homeless to Harvard',
                'content' => "At sixteen, I was living in my car. My mother's addiction had spiraled, and I had nowhere else to go. I showered at the YMCA and did homework under streetlights.\n\nMy English teacher noticed I was wearing the same clothes every day. Instead of calling CPS, she called me into her office and asked how she could help.\n\nThat conversation changed my life. She connected me with resources, helped me apply for scholarships, and wrote college recommendations that made me cry.\n\nFive years later, I walked through Harvard's gates as a freshman. I called her from my dorm room that night.\n\n\"You saw me,\" I told her. \"When no one else did, you saw me.\"",
                'excerpt' => 'One teacher\'s compassion helped a homeless teen reach the Ivy League.',
                'category' => 'inspiration',
                'author_type' => AuthorType::Self,
                'tags' => ['education', 'homelessness', 'mentorship', 'overcoming'],
