            [
                'title' => 'Running Water',
                'content' => "I spent three months volunteering in a village without running water. Every day, women and children walked miles to fill jugs from a river. Every drop was precious.\n\nWhen I came home, I stood in my shower and cried. Clean water, falling endlessly, at the perfect temperature. I'd never thought about it before—it was just always there.\n\nNow I never take a shower without thinking of those women. I never waste water without remembering what it costs. Gratitude lives in the details we usually ignore.",
                'excerpt' => 'Volunteering abroad transformed her relationship with water.',
                'category' => 'gratitude',
                'author_type' => AuthorType::Self,
                'tags' => ['volunteering', 'perspective', 'water', 'privilege'],
            ],
            [
                'title' => 'The Teacher I Finally Thanked',
                'content' => "For twenty years, I'd been meaning to write to Mrs. Chen, my high school art teacher. She saw potential in me when I saw none. She let me stay late in the art room when home wasn't safe. She wrote the recommendation that got me into college.\n\nI kept putting off that letter. Then I saw her obituary.\n\nThe grief was crushing—not just for her death, but for my years of silence. I'd meant to thank her eventually. Eventually never came.\n\nNow I write thank you letters immediately. I call people to tell them they matter. I refuse to let gratitude wait for \"someday\" again.",
                'excerpt' => 'A lesson in not waiting to express thanks.',
                'category' => 'gratitude',
