            [
                'title' => 'The Privilege of Boredom',
                'content' => "My grandmother survived a war. She fled her country with nothing, lost half her family, spent years not knowing if she'd live another day.\n\nWhen I complained about being bored one afternoon, she smiled. \"Boredom,\" she said, \"means you are safe. It means no one is chasing you, no bombs are falling, no one you love is dying.\"\n\nI never saw boredom the same way again. Now, when nothing exciting is happening, I pause. This ordinary, uneventful moment? My grandmother would have given anything for it.\n\nBoredom is a privilege. And I'm finally grateful for it.",
                'excerpt' => 'A grandmother\'s wisdom reframed the meaning of boredom.',
                'category' => 'gratitude',
