            // KINDNESS (13 stories)
            [
                'title' => 'The Coffee Shop Angel',
                'content' => "The woman in front of me at the coffee shop paid for my order. \"Pass it on,\" she said with a wink before leaving.\n\nIt was just a five-dollar coffee. But that morning, I was struggling. My bank account was nearly empty, I'd just lost my job, and I'd treated myself to coffee as a small comfort.\n\nHer kindness made me cry in the parking lot. Not because of the money, but because someone saw a stranger and chose to be generous anyway.\n\nI pass it on every chance I get now. You never know what someone is carrying or how much a small gesture might mean.",
                'excerpt' => 'A stranger\'s five-dollar kindness arrived at the perfect moment.',
                'category' => 'kindness',
                'author_type' => AuthorType::Self,
                'tags' => ['strangers', 'generosity', 'coffee', 'pay-it-forward'],
            ],
            [
                'title' => 'The Boy Who Sat Alone',
                'content' => "My son noticed a boy sitting alone at lunch every day. No one talked to him. No one sat with him. He just ate in silence and left.\n\nWithout any prompting from us, my son started sitting with him. At first, the boy didn't talk. But my son kept showing up, day after day, just being present.\n\nWeeks later, the boy started talking. Months later, they were best friends. The boy's mother called me crying, thanking us. Her son had been contemplating suicide. My son's simple kindness—just sitting with him—had given him a reason to stay.\n\nNever underestimate the power of showing up.",
                'excerpt' => 'A child\'s simple act of sitting with someone saved a life.',
                'category' => 'kindness',
                'author_type' => AuthorType::Self,
                'tags' => ['children', 'friendship', 'loneliness', 'suicide-prevention'],
            ],
            [
                'title' => 'The Mechanic\'s Gift',
                'content' => "My car broke down three states from home. I pulled into the nearest mechanic, terrified of what it would cost—money I didn't have.\n\nThe mechanic, an older man named Earl, looked at my car and then at me. \"It's a simple fix,\" he said. \"Won't take long.\"\n\nAn hour later, he handed me my keys. \"No charge.\" I protested. He shook his head. \"Someone helped me once when I was stranded. This is how I pay it back.\"\n\nI send Earl a Christmas card every year. And I've stopped to help three stranded motorists since then. His kindness keeps multiplying.",
                'excerpt' => 'A mechanic\'s generosity set off a chain of kindness.',
                'category' => 'kindness',
                'author_type' => AuthorType::Self,
                'tags' => ['strangers', 'generosity', 'cars', 'pay-it-forward'],
            ],
            [
                'title' => 'Flowers for No Reason',
                'content' => "Every Friday, my grandfather bought my grandmother flowers. Not for birthdays, not for anniversaries—just because it was Friday.\n\n\"She doesn't need a reason to feel loved,\" he'd say. \"She should feel it all the time.\"\n\nThey were married for fifty-three years. When he passed, we found a drawer full of the cards he'd written her—one for every bouquet, decades of tiny love notes.\n\nNow I buy my spouse flowers every Friday. It's a small thing, but small things add up. And love expressed is always better than love assumed.",
                'excerpt' => 'A grandfather\'s Friday tradition taught lasting lessons about love.',
                'category' => 'kindness',
                'author_type' => AuthorType::Self,
                'tags' => ['marriage', 'grandparents', 'love', 'traditions'],
